olicy makers have argued that, since then, it has entered a ‘new beginning’. This book critically examines the evidence for and against this claim. Joe Darden analyses whether Detroit’s patterns of race and class neighbourhood inequality have persisted or whether investments have led to improvements in academic achievement, homeownership, employment, and reductions in poverty and violent crime. He measures, quantitatively, the benefits and disadvantages of staying in urban Detroit or moving to the suburbs, and provides evidence to answer whether Detroit, after bankruptcy, is becoming an inclusive city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxEconomic conditionszMichiganzDetroit. 0aAfrican AmericansxHousingzMichiganzDetroit. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311119679440uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781529235685?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529235685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529235685/original  a978-3-11-119679-4  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles